aluanhaddad:
@rdettai Your intuition is correct. The generic type passed to Promise.constructor is actually misleading. It is used to create a promise of the desired type so that the type is propagated through .then. Your approach is clearer as to intent, and is more idiomatic.
Personally, I would prefer to leverage type inference all the way throughout the method to avoid misleading and potentially unsafe type assertions.
``` TypeScript
export interface Hero {
  name: string;
  powers: string[];
}
@Injectable() export class Service {
getHeroesSlowly() {
    return new Promise(resolve => {
          setTimeout(resolve, 2000);
      })
      .then(() => this.getHeroes());
  }
getHeroes(): Hero[] {
    return [{
      name: 'Wolverine',
      powers: [
        'Adamantium Claws', 
        'Mutant Healing'
      ]
    }];
  }
}
```
Letting the inference do more work leads to more type checking and more specific types.
. @wardbell that's fair since the IDE isn't there to serve up the signature in the example.
However, it leads people into the practice of placing these annotations. With generics this can be problematic because TypeScript's generics are unsafely covariant. So a Promise<void> will happily convert to a Promise<any> and mislead the caller into thinking they would get a result back.. @wardbell The difference between structural and nominal typing is completely orthogonal to the notion of type safety, strictness, and staticness. It certainly has nothing to do with the issue in question..

